- Thu 20 Dec 2018. Epidemiological situation report, DRC Ministry of Health
[in French, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://us13.campaign-archive.com/?u=89e5755d2cca4840b1af93176&id=4ea3e9cc12

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease in the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri dated 19 Dec 2018:
- Since the beginning of the epidemic, the cumulative number of cases is 560 [see above, 563], of which 512 are confirmed and 48 are probable. In total, there have bee 336 deaths (288 in confirmed and 48 in probable cases) and 193 people have recovered.
- 87 suspected cases are under investigation.
- 6 new confirmed cases, including 2 in Komanda, 1 in Katwa, 1 in Butembo, 1 in Kalunguta and 1 in Beni.
- 5 confirmed cases of Komanda (4 deaths and 1 live) from 17 Dec 2018 were added today [20 Dec 2018] due to a delay in data transmission.
- 6 new confirmed case deaths, including 3 in Beni (1 community death), 2 in Butembo and 1 in Komanda (1 community death).

News of the response
Field visits
------------
- The minister of health, Dr Oly Ilunga Kalenga, made a 4 day mission this week to Beni, Goma and Butembo. The purpose of the mission was to assess the challenges and needs to facilitate the implementation of the update of the National Response Plan 2 (Strategic Response Plan 2.1) and prepare the National Response Plan 3, which will cover the period from February through April 2019. The National Response Plan 2 (November 2018 through January 2019) was updated during December [2018] to take into account new technical and financial requirements related to the evolution of the epidemic. This constant adaptation of the national strategy demonstrates the dynamic nature of this response to the most complex Ebola outbreak in the country's history.
- The revised response plan aims to integrate all participants in the local health system in the response and strengthening of the health system. In Goma, the minister held working meetings with the Provincial Health Division of North Kivu to ensure better leadership of the provincial health authorities in overseeing the operations of the response. In Butembo, the minister visited the new local coordinating committees in the health zones of Katwa and Butembo to better anchor the response in the community. The minister then arrived in Beni on Thu 20 Dec 2018, where the new measures put in place in October [2018] have significantly reduced the number of Ebola cases in the city, which reported only one case in the past 5 days.
- He took advantage of his visit to the city to attend the grand finale of the football tournament "Ebola Pas Chez Moi", where the best teams of Beni and Butembo met to win the Cup of Hope. After launching the tournament 2 weeks ago, the minister was able to present the cup to the winners, the Cafe Sport team from Beni. He warmly congratulated all 47 teams of young footballers from Beni and Butembo who, beyond their athletic prowess, were also brand ambassadors for the youth response in these 2 big cities of North Kivu.

Vaccination
-----------
- Continued wide-belt vaccination (or ring plus) in Otomaber (in Komanda Health Zone) and Aloya (in Mabalako Health Zone).
- Continued immunization of primary care providers in the Goma Health Zone.
- Since vaccination began on 8 Aug 2018, 49 940 people have been vaccinated [see the source URL for complete breakdown of numbers vaccinated and where].

--
